Connect to AWS ✅

Browser
  ↓
CloudFront (origin group: EC2 primary, S3 fallback secondary)
  ↓
EC2 t3 instance
  ├── FastAPI app (serves API + maybe frontend)
  ├── MobileSAM model loaded in app (via ultralytics or mobile_sam package)
  └── Idle-tracking: FastAPI middleware logs last-request time → writes to DynamoDB or local file
  
CloudWatch Alarm → watches CPUUtilization/NetworkIn → stops EC2 when idle

API Gateway + Lambda (start function) → triggered by S3 fallback page → starts EC2

S3 bucket → static "waking up" page with polling JS

FastAPI-specific pieces to plan

Model loading: load MobileSAM once at startup (not per-request) — matters more on CPU where load time is non-trivial
Health check endpoint: /health — CloudFront/polling page uses this to know when the instance is truly ready (not just booted, but model loaded)
Idle tracking: since MobileSAM inference could take a few seconds, make sure your idle-detection threshold (CPU-based) doesn't accidentally treat "processing a request" as "idle" — CPU-based CloudWatch alarms are actually good here since active inference will show CPU spikes
CORS: since browser calls FastAPI directly (or via CloudFront), configure CORS properly on the FastAPI side

build order ---->

Get FastAPI + MobileSAM running on t3, confirm it works and time the inference 
Add /health endpoint
Set up CloudWatch idle-stop alarm
Build start Lambda + API Gateway
Build S3 wake-up fallback page
Wire CloudFront origin group
End-to-end test

Origin 1 (primary): your EC2/ALB origin
Origin 2 (fallback): the S3 bucket
Failover criteria: 500, 502, 503, 504
Important: set custom error response TTL low (0-10s) for those status codes so CloudFront doesn't cache the failure and keep serving stale "down" responses once the instance is back


